You want to share your study app with others via a link that they can open from Google or any browser. To do that, the app needs to be hosted online so that it has a public URL.

I created a fully self-contained single HTML file which can run locally in a browser but isn't online by default.

The best way to achieve your goal is to host this HTML file online, for example on GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or any static site hosting service. They provide a free public URL you can share.

Since I cannot deploy it for you, I will provide you instructions to deploy the HTML file on GitHub Pages. This is a common and free way to get a shareable link quickly.

Plan:

  • Briefly explain how to create a GitHub repository, add this HTML file, and enable GitHub Pages.
  • Explain how to get the public URL you can paste/share anywhere, including Google search or messages.

I will proceed with writing that helpful, actionable instruction for you now.

To share your study app with a link you can paste anywhere (like Google, chat, or emails), you need to host it online. A quick and free solution is to use GitHub Pages:

How to host your study app using GitHub Pages:

  1. Create a GitHub account (if you don’t have one):
    https://github.com/join

  2. Create a new repository:

    • Go to https://github.com/new
    • Name it (e.g. my-study-app)
    • Choose Public
    • Initialize with a README (optional)
    • Click Create repository

  3. Add your HTML file:

    • Click “Add file” → “Upload files”
    • Upload your full study-app.html file (name it index.html so it loads by default)
    • Commit changes

  4. Enable GitHub Pages:

    • Go to the repository’s “Settings” tab
    • Scroll down to “Pages” on the left sidebar
    • Under “Source,” select the main branch (or master if that is your default) and folder / (root)
    • Click “Save”
    • GitHub will provide a URL like https://yourusername.github.io/my-study-app/

  5. Open that URL in any web browser:
    Your Study App will load instantly and can be shared anywhere.

Bonus:

  • You can update the app anytime by uploading a new version of your index.html in GitHub.
  • The link is permanent unless you delete or rename your repo.
  • You can share it on Google by submitting the link to Google Search Console if you want indexing.

If you want, I can provide the exact full HTML file index.html content ready for upload or help you with other hosting options. Just let me know!

Step-by-Step Guide to Create a New GitHub Repository

  1. Log in to GitHub:

    • Go to GitHub and log in to your account. If you don’t have an account, you can sign up for free.

  2. Create a New Repository:

    • Once logged in, click on the "+" icon in the top right corner of the page.
    • Select "New repository" from the dropdown menu.

  3. Fill in Repository Details:

    • Repository Name: Enter a name for your repository (e.g., my-study-app).
    • Description (optional): You can add a brief description of your project (e.g., "A study app with a football theme").
    • Public/Private: Choose Public so that anyone can view it.
    • Initialize this repository with a README (optional): You can check this box if you want to create a README file

I'll guide you step-by-step to create your GitHub repository and upload your study app HTML file.

How to Create a GitHub Repository and Upload Your File

  1. Go to GitHub
    Open your browser and go to https://github.com.
    If you don’t have an account, click Sign up and create one.

  2. Create a new repository

    • After logging in, click the "+" icon in the top-right corner (near your profile picture).
    • Click New repository.

  3. Fill repository details

    • Repository name: Type something like my-study-app.
    • (Optional) Write a description.
    • Choose Public so it can be accessed by anyone.
    • (Optional) Check Add a README file.
    • Click Create repository.

  4. Upload your HTML file

    • On the new repository page, you will see the option Add file → click Upload files.
    • Drag and drop your study-app.html file or browse to select it.
    • Rename the file to index.html before uploading (important so GitHub Pages loads it by default).
    • Scroll down and click Commit changes.

  5. Enable GitHub Pages

    • Click on the Settings tab (top menu).
    • Scroll down the left sidebar and click Pages.
    • Under Source, select main (or the default branch), and set the folder to / (root).
    • Click Save.
    • After a few seconds, you will see a link like https://yourusername.github.io/my-study-app/.

  6. Open your Study App

    • Click the link to open your app in the browser.
    • You can share this link anywhere, on Google, chat, or email.
